<br>
So we assume that a successfull taunt will put yourself on top of the hate list + something over.<br>
<br>
Now, it often happen that you are the one getting attacked, but not necessarilly the top &quot;hater&quot; on the list.  The mob will often attack the pc when he is the most &quot;convenient&quot; to attack at this moment (close by for example).  Let's take this reverse example a bit :<br>
<br>
You have 2 tanks on 1 mob.  1 is holding aggro fairly well, tank A.  For some reason the mob is moving to a firepot and tank A want to move the mob elsewhere.  Tank A move himself but the mob does not follow and decide to hit tank B instead.  As soon as tank A come back into melee range he get attacked again as he is the one with the most hate.  It's pretty clear that in this example that when tank A is out of range, even thought tank B is taking the hits, he could gain a significant chunks of aggro &quot;points&quot; by doing a successfull taunt that would put him over tank A hate and also as a convenient close target.<br>
<br>
Now, if tank A's hate was significantly over tank B's hate when tank A decided to move the mob, then the mob would have followed and not hit tank B because it was hating him too much.<br>
<br>
Basically there is a threshold of hate points where the mob will simply stay on the same target unless the threshold is broke.  Keeping the speculation on, that threshold will increase if the npc and pc are at a distance for each other.  Snare will also increase the strenght of the &quot;distance threshold&quot; by making it even more inconvenient for the mob to move to the target on top of the list.<br>
<br>
If someone break that threshold over the current hate holder, then the mob will do whatever it can to get to that pc.  Summon first, then pong until summon recycle, etc.<br>
<br>
So you can apply that logic to tank vs caster aggro.  What this mean is a caster could cast a spell and get first on the aggro list with that mob without getting over the threshold because of distance or whatever.  It would be worthwhile for the tank at this time to taunt and try to get instantly back on top of the list even thought it's apparent to him he never lost aggro.<br>
<br>
Because most of this stuff is transparent till someone actually steal the hate from the tank, you have the option of simply &quot;mashing&quot; the button.<br>
<br>
Anyhow, it's more complex then some of you might think.<br>
<br>
Don't forget the usual disclaimer, not facts, speculation, opinions, blah, blah, blah.<br>
<br>
Thorbadin<br>
