<br>
We assume that you have a real aggro on 1 list that get modified by spells, hiting and taunt + other usual stuff.<br>
<br>
You also have the modified aggro list based on the normal list that get affected by siting, range, hp of target, mob snared, etc.<br>
<br>
Let's say that being oor reduce your aggro in half in the modified list as an easy example.<br>
<br>
-Tank got 1000 aggro pts with melee and his tanking.<br>
-Caster got 0/2 for being oor, still 0.<br>
<br>
=&gt; Caster nuke for 800 hate.<br>
-tank still at 1000.<br>
-Caster now at 800/2 : 400 hate cause oor.<br>
<br>
Worth it to taunt? No cause real hate is 1000 vs 800, melee still tanking.<br>
<br>
=&gt; caster nuke for 800 more hate.<br>
-tank still at 1000.<br>
-Caster at 1600/2 : 800 hate cause oor.<br>
<br>
Worth it to taunt?  Real hate of caster in that example is greater then the melee, so a sucessfull taunt will give the tank an extra 601+ hate, moving him from 1000 to 1601+.<br>
<br>
-Assuming taunt doesnt work this time, another nuke will make the caster aggro the mob and pong/summon him.<br>
<br>
-If taunt did work the previous time, even thought the melee never stop tanking, his new found hate will prevent the caster for overaggroing with a 3rd nuke.<br>
<br>
It's a simplistic example, but assuming it work that way it should hold true.<br>
<br>
It could also not be the case, like it would be easy to prevent a succesfull taunt to go over the aggro on modified list to prevent the building aggro syndrome.  It could also work that way as it would explain some of the stuff we see.<br>
<br>
How's that one?<br>
<br>
Thorbadin<br>
